@Node "__sys_errlist"
__sys_errlist-Errno text strings

Synopsis

   #include <errno.h>

   extern char *__sys_errlist[];

Description

   The external array of strings __sys_errlist provides the text message
   that corresponds to a given @{" errno " Link "errno"}.  The value of @{" errno " Link "errno"} is used as a
   direct index to this table.  You should not access this table directly,
   but instead use the @{" perror() " Link "perror()"} or @{" strerror() " Link "strerror()"} functions.  You may wish
   to substitute your own table for internationalization of your program.
   The external integer @{" __sys_nerr " Link "__sys_nerr"} indicates the number of entries in
   the table.

   In versions 5.10 and earlier, this variable was named sys_errlist.

Portability

   @{" SAS/C " Link "Glossary - SASC"}

See Also

   @{" perror() " Link "perror()"} , @{" strerror() " Link "strerror()"} , @{" __sys_nerr " Link "__sys_nerr"}
@EndNode

@Node "__sys_nerr"
__sys_nerr-Number of entries in __sys_errlist

Synopsis

   #include <errno.h>

   extern int __sys_nerr;

Description

   The external integer __sys_nerr indicates the number of entries in the
   @{" __sys_errlist " Link "__sys_errlist"} array.  It should be declared at the same time as the
   @{" __sys_errlist " Link "__sys_errlist"} array to indicate which messages are available for
   @{" perror() " Link "perror()"} and @{" strerror() " Link "strerror()"}.

   In versions 5.10 and earlier, this variable was named sys_nerr.

Portability

   @{" SAS/C " Link "Glossary - SASC"}

See Also

   @{" perror() " Link "perror()"} , @{" strerror() " Link "strerror()"} , @{" __sys_errlist " Link "__sys_errlist"}
@EndNode

