__tzname-timezone names

Synopsis

   extern char *__tzname[2];

Description

   The two __tzname pointers point to __tzstn and __tzdtn, respectively.
   These strings contain the three-character names for standard time
   (@{" __tzstn " Link "__tzstn"}) and daylight time (@{" __tzdtn " Link "__tzdtn"}).  These variables are
   initialized by the @{" __tzset() " Link "__tzset()"} function and used by the @{" localtime() " Link "localtime()"}
   function to adjust from Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) to the local time.

Portability

   @{" UNIX " Link "Glossary - UNIX"}

See Also

   @{" __daylight " Link "__daylight"} , @{" localtime() " Link "localtime()"} , @{" __timezone " Link "__timezone"} , @{" __tzdtn " Link "__tzdtn"} ,
   @{" __tzset() " Link "__tzset()"} , @{" __tzstn " Link "__tzstn"}
@EndNode

@Node "__tzset()"
__tzset()-Set time zone variable

Synopsis

   #include <time.h>

   void __tzset(void);

   If the @{" _STRICT_ANSI " Link "_STRICT_ANSI"} flag has not been defined, these symbols are
   defined in time.h:

   extern int __daylight;
   extern long __timezone;
   extern char *__tzname[2];
   extern char __tzstn[4];
   extern char __tzdtn[4];
   extern char *_TZ;

Portability

   XENIX

See Also

   @{" time.h " Link "time.h"} , @{" localtime() " Link "localtime()"}
@EndNode

@Node "__tzstn"
__tzstn-Standard time name

Synopsis

   extern char __tzstn[4];

Description

   __tzstn contains the three-character name for standard time.  This
   variable is initialized by the @{" __tzset() " Link "__tzset()"} function and used by the
   @{" localtime() " Link "localtime()"} function to adjust from Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) to
   local time.

Portability

   @{" SAS/C " Link "Glossary - SASC"}

See Also

   @{" __daylight " Link "__daylight"} , @{" localtime() " Link "localtime()"} , @{" __timezone " Link "__timezone"} , @{" __tzname " Link "__tzname"} ,
   @{" __tzdtn " Link "__tzdtn"} , @{" __tzset() " Link "__tzset()"}
@EndNode

@Node "__ufbs"
__ufbs-Array of open level 1 file handles

Synopsis

   #include <ios1.h>

   extern struct UFB *__ufbs;

Description

   The external array __ufbs is used to track all open level 1 file
   handles.  The number returned by @{" open() " Link "open()"} or @{" creat() " Link "creat()"} is an index into
   this table.   The external variable __nufbs indicates the number of
   elements in the __ufbs array.

   You should never index this array directly.  The @{" chkufb() " Link "chkufb()"} function is
   provided to translate an index into the appropriate UFB structure.

   In versions 5.10 and earlier, this array was named _ufbs.

Portability

   @{" SAS/C " Link "Glossary - SASC"}

See Also

   @{" chkufb() " Link "chkufb()"} , @{" creat() " Link "creat()"} , @{" __nufbs " Link "__nufbs"} , @{" open() " Link "open()"}
@EndNode

@Node "ungetc()"
ungetc()-Push input character back

Synopsis

   #include <stdio.h>

   r = ungetc(c, fp);

   int r;      /* return character or code */
   int c;      /* character to be pushed back */
   FILE *fp;   /* file pointer */

Portability

   @{" ANSI " Link "Glossary - ANSI"}

Returns

   Normally, ungetc() returns the character that was pushed back.
   However, if the end-of-file has been reached or if no characters have
   been read yet, the value EOF is returned.

See Also

   @{" getc() " Link "getc()"}
@EndNode

@Node "unlink()"
unlink()-remove a file

Synopsis

   #include <stdio.h>

   error = unlink(name);

   int error;          /* non-zero if error */
   const char *name;   /* file name */

Portability

   @{" UNIX " Link "Glossary - UNIX"}

Returns

   If a non-zero value is returned, some type of error occurred, and
   additional information can be found in @{" errno " Link "errno"} and @{" _OSERR " Link "_OSERR"}.  The most
   common errors occur when you try to remove a file that doesn't exist,
   that is marked as read-only, or that is in use.

See Also

   @{" errno " Link "errno"} , @{" _OSERR " Link "_OSERR"} , @{" remove() " Link "remove()"}
@EndNode

@Node "utpack()"
utpack()-Pack @{" UNIX " Link "Glossary - UNIX"} time

Synopsis

   #include <time.h>

   ut = utpack(x);

   long ut;         /* packed UNIX time */
   const char *x;   /* unpacked UNIX time */

Portability

   @{" SAS/C " Link "Glossary - SASC"}

Returns

   This function returns a packed long, as described above.

See Also

   @{" ctime() " Link "ctime()"} , @{" getclk() " Link "getclk()"} , @{" gmtime() " Link "gmtime()"} , @{" localtime() " Link "localtime()"} ,
   @{" stpdate() " Link "stpdate()"} , @{" time() " Link "time()"} , @{" utunpk() " Link "utunpk()"}
@EndNode

@Node "utunpk()"
utunpk()-Unpack @{" UNIX " Link "Glossary - UNIX"} time

